Hey dude, let's play with making library.

Let's do some experiment.

Fisrt, you do this.

$ cd src
$ gcc -c cfg.c common.c line_data.c
cfg.c  cfg.h  cfg.o  common.c  common.h  common.o  line_data.c  line_data.h  line_data.o  main.c

As you can see, you get .o files.

Next, you do this.

$ ar crv sosreport-analyzer.a cfg.o common.o line_data.o
a - cfg.o
a - common.o
a - line_data.o

Check the result.

$ ls
cfg.c  cfg.h  cfg.o  common.c  common.h  common.o  line_data.c  line_data.h  line_data.o  main.c  sosreport-analyzer.a

You get sosreport-analyzer.a.

Now, you do this.

$ gcc -c main.c
$ ls
cfg.c  cfg.h  cfg.o  common.c  common.h  common.o  line_data.c  line_data.h  line_data.o  main.c  main.o  sosreport-analyzer.a

So, let's make a program which is useful.

$ gcc -o sosreport-analyzer-ng main.o sosreport-analyzer.a 
$ ls
cfg.c  cfg.h  cfg.o  common.c  common.h  common.o  line_data.c  line_data.h  line_data.o  main.c  main.o  sosreport-analyzer-ng  sosreport-analyzer.a

You can use 'sosreport-analyzer-ng' in current directory.

But, alert, you should have sosreport-analyzer.conf.

You shoul copy sosreport-analyzer.conf.example to /etc/sosreport-analyzer.conf


Wait...
